(* array  option  result                                       *)


(* ----------------------------------------------------------------- *)
(*  Operator precedence summary (high to low)                        *)
(*  Encoded structurally in the expression grammar above.            *)
(* ----------------------------------------------------------------- *)

(*
    Level   Operators                           Associativity
    ------  --------------------------------    -------------
    13      postfix: . [] () ? as              left
    12      unary:   - ~ * & &mut              right
    11      * / % *% *|                        left
    10      + - +% -% +| -|                   left
    9       == != < <= > >= in not in          left (non-associative)
    8       not                                right
    7       and                                left
    6       or                                 left
    5       | (pipe)                           left
    4       => (lambda body)                   right
    3       = += -= etc (assignment stmts)     right  [statement only]
*)


(* ----------------------------------------------------------------- *)
(*  Disambiguation notes                                              *)
(* ----------------------------------------------------------------- *)

(*
  1.  "|" is overloaded: it appears in sum type declarations,
      or-patterns, and the pipe operator in expressions. The parser
      disambiguates by context:
        - Inside a "type" RHS at statement level: sum body variant.
        - Inside a "match" arm LHS: or-pattern.
        - Inside an expression: pipe operator.

  2.  "[" is overloaded: it begins a type argument list (named_type),
      an array literal (array_expr), a slice type (slice_type), and
      an index expression (postfix_suffix).

      In type position the reading is unambiguous: only type_arg_list
      and slice_type are available, and they differ in whether a
      module_path precedes the bracket.

      In expression position "base [ ... ]" is either indexing or a
      compile-time argument list. The reading is decided by what "base"
      names, in this order:

        a.  If "base" resolves in the value namespace — a local binding,
            a parameter, or a static — the brackets are INDEXING. A value
            shadowing a generic name means the value was meant.
        b.  Otherwise, if "base" names a type or a generic callable, the
            brackets are a COMPILE-TIME ARGUMENT LIST.
        c.  Within a compile-time argument list, each argument's meaning
            is fixed by the DECLARATION's parameter in that position, not
            by the argument's own syntax: a "[n: usize]" parameter takes
            a value argument, a bare "[T]" parameter takes a type
            argument. So "f[list[int32]]" and "f[3]" need no syntactic
            distinction — the declaration of "f" already says which is
            expected, and a mismatch is a diagnosable error.
        d.  Anything else is an error. There is no fallback to indexing.

      Rule (c) is what lets a type argument be an arbitrary type_expr,
      including a nested generic application, without the bracket
      contents having to be classifiable on their own.

      Type arguments are NOT written with angle brackets. "<>" would put
      the ambiguity in the comparison operators ("a < b, c > (d)" is both
      a valid expression and a valid instantiation), which no namespace
      lookup can resolve; the "[" ambiguity above is settled by a single
      lookup because types and values occupy separate namespaces. See
      spec/generic-inference-design.md §4.1.

  3.  "static" begins static declarations, static-if, static-assert,
      static-for, and the static_expr form inside expressions. The
      token following "static" determines which production applies.

  4.  Backtick quote regions may contain any Kira tokens including
      nested quotes and splice expressions. The parser maintains a
      quote depth counter; a "~" at depth > 0 is a splice, at depth
      0 it is a unary operator.

  5.  NEWLINE suppression: NEWLINE tokens are suppressed inside any
      balanced bracket pair ( ), [ ], { }, or a backtick quote
      region. This allows multi-line expressions without explicit
      line continuation.

  6.  func_modifier ordering: the canonical order is
        [static] [pure] [async[...]] [machine]
      The parser accepts any order and the semantic checker enforces
      valid combinations. Invalid combinations (e.g. static machine)
      are a semantic error, not a parse error.

  7.  "~" unary operator vs splice: at expression-level depth 0,
      "~" followed by "(" is a splice_expr; "~" followed by anything
      else is a bitwise-complement unary operator. Inside a quote
      region, "~" always begins a splice.

  8.  The "module_path" in a named_type may be a single IDENT,
      making it identical to an expression IDENT reference. The
      parser treats it uniformly; the type-checker resolves whether
      it names a type or a value.

  9.  "type_expr" in match_subject (compile-time type match) is only
      valid when the match is in a static context or the subject is
      a type parameter. The parser accepts it; semantic analysis
      rejects it outside static context.

  10. The for_expr (expression form) uses "=>" to denote the yield
      expression. This is distinct from the for_stmt (statement
      form) which uses ":". The lexer sees the same token stream;
      the parser disambiguates by whether "=>" or ":" follows the
      optional "if" guard.

  11. "@" marks a sum-type variant constructor uniformly wherever one
      occurs: declaration (sum_variant), construction (variant_expr),
      and pattern matching (atomic_pattern), including inside "if let"
      and "while let". A bare IDENT is therefore never a constructor —
      in an expression it is a variable reference, in a pattern it is
      always a fresh binding. "@" needs no lookahead or symbol-table
      lookup to disambiguate: the token alone determines the production.
*)
